COMPONENT NAME: LKM Oracle to Oracle (DBLINK)
AUTHOR: Oracle
Description: - Loading Knowledge Module - Loads data from an Oracle instance to another Oracle Instance using database links. - This module is recommended when developing interfaces between two Oracle servers. - A view is created on the source server and a synonym on this view is created on the target server. - When using this module on a journalized source table, the Journaling table is first updated to flag the records consumed and then cleaned from these records at the end of the interface.
Restrictions: - The 'tnsnames.ora' configuration file of the target server should be configured to recognize the source database. The source database entry in tnsnames.ora file should have name as "Instance/dblink (Data Server)" defined in the Topology for Source schema data server.
- The database link name used by this LKM is the name of the "Instance/dblink (Data Server)" defined in the Topology for Source schema data server. If AUTO_CREATE_DB_LINK is set to false (default), the link with this name should exist in the target schema and created as: create public database link <Instance/dblink (Data Server) name> connect to <system user> identified by <system password> using <Instance/dblink (Data Server) name>
If AUTO_CREATE_DB_LINK is set to true, db link will be automatically created on the target schema.
- The work schema of the source instance must have 'select any table' privilege set.
Limitation: - when using this LKM for the same instance, make sure that the 2 servers defined in the Topology have different "Instance/dblink (Data Server)" values and corresponding entries in the tnsnames.ora
Set this option to NO if you wish to retain temporary indexes after integration. This could be useful when the same sources tables are used in differents interfaces of a package.

Set this option to NO if you wish to retain temporary objects (files and scripts) after integration. Useful for debugging.
NB : Database links are managed by the AUTO_CREATE_DB_LINK option in order to avoid an unexpected deletion

In case you use this LKM in an Oracle DB 11R2 or later environment with Editions activated and data is accessed through editioning views instead of directly through tables, you should consider activating this option. Please see KM reference guide for details.

If AUTO_CREATE_DB_LINK is set to true, db link will be automatically created on the target schema. If AUTO_CREATE_DB_LINK is set to false (default), the link with this name should exist in the target schema.
